{"id": "duc04-testb-14:6#18", "contents": "As NATO attacks loom, top U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke delivered a stern warning to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Monday, urging him to halt his crackdown on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo or face airstrikes. However, there was no indication that Milosevic was backing down. After meeting with Holbrooke, Milosevic's office issued a statement denouncing NATO threats as a \"criminal act\" favoring separatist ethnic Albanian guerrillas. The statement claimed there had been no fighting in Kosovo for the past seven days and that the crisis posed no threat to other Balkan countries. Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador-designate to the United Nations, met with Milosevic for several hours, emphasizing the \"extreme gravity of the situation.\""}
